# Data Access & API Conventions

How data flows in softwhere.uz: databases behind repositories, feature HTTP calls behind module `api` modules, and one generic HTTP client in `core`. The old "migrate `fetch()` to `src/utils/api.ts`" guide is obsolete — that file never existed post-refactor. Use the patterns below instead.

## At a glance

| Need | Use | Location |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Read/write the DB | A repository function | `src/modules/*/model/*.repository.ts` |
| Call an internal/external HTTP endpoint | A module `api` wrapper, else `apiClient` | `src/modules/*/api*.ts`, `src/core/http.ts` |
| Response/error types | `ApiResponse<T>`, `AppError` | `src/core/http.ts` |
| Admin browser calls (auth cookie) | `adminFetch` | `src/modules/admin/utils/adminFetch.ts` |

## 1. Database access — the repository layer

Drizzle and the `db` client (`src/core/db.ts`) are imported **only** by repository files. Routes, pages, and other modules call exported repository functions; they never build queries themselves.

- `src/modules/blog/model/posts.repository.ts` — `blog_posts` reads/writes (`listPublished`, `getPublishedBySlug`, `createPost`, `updateById`, `deleteById`, `listForAdmin`, `pingDb`, ...).
- `src/modules/contact/model/leads.repository.ts` — `leads` reads/writes (`createLead`, `markLeadNotified`, `listLeads`).

```typescript
// src/app/[locale]/blog/[slug]/page.tsx
import * as postsRepo from '@/modules/blog/model/posts.repository';

const post = await postsRepo.getPublishedBySlugFlexible(slug, locale);
```

Repositories return already-serialized shapes (e.g. `IBlogPost` with `_id` and ISO-string dates from `serializePost` in `src/modules/blog/model/BlogPost.ts`), so callers stay decoupled from raw DB rows.

## 2. Feature HTTP calls — module `api` modules

Feature-specific HTTP calls live next to their module and build on the core client. Client-only files here are distinct from the server-only generation code in the same folder.

- `src/modules/blog/api/posts.ts` — `getRelatedPost(generationGroupId, locale)` (client). The generator (`api/generator.ts`, `api/pipeline.ts`) in the same directory is **server-only**.
- `src/modules/estimator/api.ts` — `getEstimate(...)` and `submitEstimateLead(...)`.

```typescript
// src/modules/blog/api/posts.ts
import { apiClient } from '@/core/http';

export async function getRelatedPost(generationGroupId: string, locale: string) {
  return apiClient.get<{ post: { slug: string; locale: string } }>(
    `/api/blog/posts/related?generationGroupId=${generationGroupId}&locale=${locale}`
  );
}
```

When a call needs a timeout longer than the client's 10s default (e.g. the estimator's ~60s AI round), the wrapper may use a dedicated `fetch` with its own `AbortController` while still returning an `ApiResponse` — see `getEstimate` in `src/modules/estimator/api.ts`.

## 3. The generic HTTP client — `core/http`

`src/core/http.ts` exports a singleton `apiClient` (an `ApiClient` instance) plus response types and helpers. It is domain-agnostic so `core` stays free of any `shared`/`modules` dependency.

| Export | What it is |
| --- | --- |
| `apiClient` | `get` / `post` / `put` / `delete` / `patch`, each returning `Promise<ApiResponse<T>>` |
| `ApiResponse<T>` | `{ success: boolean; data?: T; error?: string; message?: string }` |
| `AppError` | `{ message: string; code?: string; status?: number }` |
| `handleApiError` | Maps a failed `ApiResponse` to an `AppError` |
| `validateApiResponse` | Returns `data` or throws the `AppError` on `!success` |

Behavior: sets `Content-Type: application/json`, logs request/response/timing via `logger`, aborts after a 10s default timeout, and normalizes non-2xx responses into `{ success: false, error }` (it never throws for HTTP errors).

```typescript
import { apiClient, validateApiResponse } from '@/core/http';

const res = await apiClient.get('/api/blog/posts');
if (res.success) {
  const posts = res.data;
}
// or, throw-on-failure:
const posts = validateApiResponse(await apiClient.get('/api/blog/posts'));
```

> `ApiResponse` and `AppError` intentionally live in `@/core/http`, not in `@/shared/types`, so that `core` does not depend on `shared`.

## 4. Admin calls from the browser

Admin UI calls go through `adminFetch` (`src/modules/admin/utils/adminFetch.ts`): it sends the Neon Auth session cookie (`credentials: 'same-origin'`), sets JSON headers when there's a body, and reloads the page on a 401 so the server-side admin gate re-shows the login form. Server route handlers still enforce access with `requireAdmin` (`src/core/auth.ts`).

## Internal API endpoints (reference)

Route handlers live under `src/app/api/**`:

| Endpoint | Handler |
| --- | --- |
| `GET /api/blog/posts`, `GET /api/blog/posts/[slug]`, `GET /api/blog/posts/related` | `src/app/api/blog/posts/**` |
| `POST /api/blog/generate` | `src/app/api/blog/generate/route.ts` |
| `GET/POST /api/admin/posts`, `/api/admin/posts/[id]`, `/api/admin/leads`, `/api/admin/revalidate` | `src/app/api/admin/**` |
| `POST /api/contact`, `POST /api/estimate`, `POST /api/estimate/lead`, `GET /api/currency/rates` | `src/app/api/**` |
| `/api/auth/[...path]` (Neon Auth), `GET /api/health`, `GET /api/health/db`, `GET /api/og` | `src/app/api/**` |

